Hi [~tangzhankun]

Sorry for this late comments. I have some worry on below code.
{code:java}
58	static int is_block_device(const char* value) {
59	int is_block = 0;
60	char* block_path = malloc(512);
61	if (snprintf(block_path, 512, "/sys/dev/block/%s",
62	 value) < 0) {
63	  fprintf(ERRORFILE, "Failed to construct system block device path.\n");
64	  goto cleanup;
65	}{code}
After malloc it's safe to do a memset with 0 on allocated block. And especially, snprintf need to follow with /0 which may be missing this case now.

cc [~leftnoteasy] if you would like to check the C code.

[~sunilg] , Thanks for mentioning this good question.

From what I know, the "snprintf" and "vsnprintf" is, in essence, a buffer copy function and will copy at most "size" (here 512) bytes including the trailing null byte ('\0'). And no "memset" needed before it. We don't need to "memset" a string before "strcopy", right?

And you can check this for details. In below example, it doesn't use "memset" or append '\0'.
{code:java}
int n;
int size = 100; /* Guess we need no more than 100 bytes */
char *p, *np;
va_list ap;
if ((p = malloc(size)) == NULL)
return NULL;
while (1) {
/* Try to print in the allocated space */
va_start(ap, fmt);
n = vsnprintf(p, size, fmt, ap);
...
{code}

 [https://linux.die.net/man/3/snprintf]

